 <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method, which returns any standard, code page, or DBCS encoding available in .NET."},{"content":"Overloads let you specify a fallback object for both the encoder and the decoder.","pos":[5630,5711]},{"pos":[5719,6471],"content":"[!NOTE]\n The Unicode Standard assigns a code point (a number) and a name to each character in every supported script. For example, the character \"A\" is represented by the code point U+0041 and the name \"LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A\". The Unicode Transformation Format (UTF) encodings define ways to encode that code point into a sequence of one or more bytes. A Unicode encoding scheme simplifies world-ready application development because it allows characters from any character set to be represented in a single encoding. Application developers no longer have to keep track of the encoding scheme that was used to produce characters for a specific language or writing system, and data can be shared among systems internationally without being corrupted.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"The Unicode Standard assigns a code point (a number) and a name to each character in every supported script. For example, the character \"A\" is represented by the code point U+0041 and the name \"LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A\". The Unicode Transformation Format (UTF) encodings define ways to encode that code point into a sequence of one or more bytes. A Unicode encoding scheme simplifies world-ready application development because it allows characters from any character set to be represented in a single encoding. Application developers no longer have to keep track of the encoding scheme that was used to produce characters for a specific language or writing system, and data can be shared among systems internationally without being corrupted.","pos":[9,750],"nodes":[{"content":"The Unicode Standard assigns a code point (a number) and a name to each character in every supported script.","pos":[0,108]},{"content":"For example, the character \"A\" is represented by the code point U+0041 and the name \"LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A\".","pos":[109,218]},{"content":"The Unicode Transformation Format (UTF) encodings define ways to encode that code point into a sequence of one or more bytes.","pos":[219,344]},{"content":"A Unicode encoding scheme simplifies world-ready application development because it allows characters from any character set to be represented in a single encoding.","pos":[345,509]},{"content":"Application developers no longer have to keep track of the encoding scheme that was used to produce characters for a specific language or writing system, and data can be shared among systems internationally without being corrupted.","pos":[510,741]}]}]},{"content":".NET supports three encodings defined by the Unicode standard: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32.","pos":[6482,6571]},{"content":"For more information, see The Unicode Standard at the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Unicode home page<ept id=\"p1\">](https://www.unicode.org/)</ept>.","pos":[6572,6672],"source":" For more information, see The Unicode Standard at the [Unicode home page](https://www.unicode.org/)."},{"content":"You can retrieve information about all the encodings available in .NET by calling the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncodings%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[6679,6845],"source":"You can retrieve information about all the encodings available in .NET by calling the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncodings%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":".NET supports the character encoding systems listed in the following table.","pos":[6846,6921]},{"content":"Encoding","pos":[6928,6936]},{"content":"Class","pos":[6937,6942]},{"content":"Description","pos":[6943,6954]},{"content":"Advantages/disadvantages","pos":[6955,6979]},{"content":"ASCII","pos":[7065,7070]},{"content":"Encodes a limited range of characters by using the lower seven bits of a byte.","pos":[7104,7182]},{"content":"Because this encoding only supports character values from U+0000 through U+007F, in most cases it is inadequate for internationalized applications.","pos":[7183,7330]},{"content":"UTF-7","pos":[7335,7340]},{"content":"Represents characters as sequences of 7-bit ASCII characters.","pos":[7373,7434]},{"content":"Non-ASCII Unicode characters are represented by an escape sequence of ASCII characters.","pos":[7435,7522]},{"content":"UTF-7 supports protocols such as email and newsgroup protocols.","pos":[7523,7586]},{"content":"However, UTF-7 is not particularly secure or robust.","pos":[7587,7639]},{"content":"In some cases, changing one bit can radically alter the interpretation of an entire UTF-7 string.","pos":[7640,7737]},{"content":"In other cases, different UTF-7 strings can encode the same text.","pos":[7738,7803]},{"content":"For sequences that include non-ASCII characters, UTF-7 requires more space than UTF-8, and encoding/decoding is slower.","pos":[7804,7923]},{"content":"Consequently, you should use UTF-8 instead of UTF-7 if possible.","pos":[7924,7988]},{"content":"UTF-8","pos":[7993,7998]},{"content":"Represents each Unicode code point as a sequence of one to four bytes.","pos":[8031,8101]},{"content":"UTF-8 supports 8-bit data sizes and works well with many existing operating systems.","pos":[8102,8186]},{"content":"For the ASCII range of characters, UTF-8 is identical to ASCII encoding and allows a broader set of characters.","pos":[8187,8298]},{"content":"However, for Chinese-Japanese-Korean (CJK) scripts, UTF-8 can require three bytes for each character, and can potentially cause larger data sizes than UTF-16.","pos":[8299,8457]},{"content":"Note that sometimes the amount of ASCII data, such as HTML tags, justifies the increased size for the CJK range.","pos":[8458,8570]},{"content":"UTF-16","pos":[8575,8581]},{"content":"Represents each Unicode code point as a sequence of one or two 16-bit integers.","pos":[8617,8696]},{"content":"Most common Unicode characters require only one UTF-16 code point, although Unicode supplementary characters (U+10000 and greater) require two UTF-16 surrogate code points.","pos":[8697,8869]},{"content":"Both little-endian and big-endian byte orders are supported.","pos":[8870,8930]},{"pos":[8931,9126],"content":"UTF-16 encoding is used by the common language runtime to represent <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Char&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.String&gt;</ph> values, and it is used by the Windows operating system to represent <ph id=\"ph3\">`WCHAR`</ph> values.","source":"UTF-16 encoding is used by the common language runtime to represent <xref:System.Char> and <xref:System.String> values, and it is used by the Windows operating system to represent `WCHAR` values."},{"content":"UTF-32","pos":[9131,9137]},{"content":"Represents each Unicode code point as a 32-bit integer.","pos":[9171,9226]},{"content":"Both little-endian and big-endian byte orders are supported.","pos":[9227,9287]},{"content":"UTF-32 encoding is used when applications want to avoid the surrogate code point behavior of UTF-16 encoding on operating systems for which encoded space is too important.","pos":[9288,9459]},{"content":"Single glyphs rendered on a display can still be encoded with more than one UTF-32 character.","pos":[9460,9553]},{"content":"ANSI/ISO encodings","pos":[9558,9576]},{"content":"Provides support for a variety of code pages.","pos":[9578,9623]},{"content":"On Windows operating systems, code pages are used to support a specific language or group of languages.","pos":[9624,9727]},{"content":"For a table that lists the code pages supported by .NET, see the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding&gt;</ph> class.","pos":[9728,9827],"source":" For a table that lists the code pages supported by .NET, see the <xref:System.Text.Encoding> class."},{"content":"You can retrieve an encoding object for a particular code page by calling the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding%28System.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[9828,10000],"source":" You can retrieve an encoding object for a particular code page by calling the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding%28System.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":"A code page contains 256 code points and is zero-based.","pos":[10001,10056]},{"content":"In most code pages, code points 0 through 127 represent the ASCII character set, and code points 128 through 255 differ significantly between code pages.","pos":[10057,10210]},{"content":"For example, code page 1252 provides the characters for Latin writing systems, including English, German, and French.","pos":[10211,10328]},{"content":"The last 128 code points in code page 1252 contain the accent characters.","pos":[10329,10402]},{"content":"Code page 1253 provides character codes that are required in the Greek writing system.","pos":[10403,10489]},{"content":"The last 128 code points in code page 1253 contain the Greek characters.","pos":[10490,10562]},{"content":"As a result, an application that relies on ANSI code pages cannot store Greek and German in the same text stream unless it includes an identifier that indicates the referenced code page.","pos":[10563,10749]},{"content":"Double-byte character set (DBCS) encodings","pos":[10754,10796]},{"content":"Supports languages, such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean, that contain more than 256 characters.","pos":[10798,10895]},{"content":"In a DBCS, a pair of code points (a double byte) represents each character.","pos":[10896,10971]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.IsSingleByte%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property returns <ph id=\"ph2\">`false`</ph> for DBCS encodings.","pos":[10972,11093],"source":" The <xref:System.Text.Encoding.IsSingleByte%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property returns `false` for DBCS encodings."},{"content":"You can retrieve an encoding object for a particular DBCS by calling the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding%28System.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[11094,11261],"source":" You can retrieve an encoding object for a particular DBCS by calling the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetEncoding%28System.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":"In a DBCS, a pair of code points (a double byte) represents each character.","pos":[11262,11337]},{"content":"When an application handles DBCS data, the first byte of a DBCS character (the lead byte) is processed in combination with the trail byte that immediately follows it.","pos":[11338,11504]},{"content":"Because a single pair of double-byte code points can represent different characters depending on the code page, this scheme still does not allow for the combination of two languages, such as Japanese and Chinese, in the same data stream.","pos":[11505,11742]},{"content":"These encodings enable you to work with Unicode characters as well as with encodings that are most commonly used in legacy applications.","pos":[11750,11886]},{"content":"In addition, you can create a custom encoding by defining a class that derives from <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding&gt;</ph> and overriding its members.","pos":[11887,12026],"source":" In addition, you can create a custom encoding by defining a class that derives from <xref:System.Text.Encoding> and overriding its members."},{"pos":[12036,12106],"content":"Platform Notes: <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[net_core](../../../includes/net-core-md.md)]</ph>","linkify":"Platform Notes: [!INCLUDE[net_core](../../../includes/net-core-md.md)]","source":"Platform Notes: [!INCLUDE[net_core](../../../includes/net-core-md.md)]"},{"content":"By default, <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[net_core](../../../includes/net-core-md.md)]</ph> does not make available any code page encodings other than code page 28591 and the Unicode encodings, such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.","pos":[12110,12304],"source":"By default, [!INCLUDE[net_core](../../../includes/net-core-md.md)] does not make available any code page encodings other than code page 28591 and the Unicode encodings, such as UTF-8 and UTF-16."},{"content":"However, you can add the code page encodings found in standard Windows apps that target .NET to your app.","pos":[12305,12410]},{"content":"For complete information, see the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.CodePagesEncodingProvider&gt;</ph> topic.","pos":[12411,12496],"source":" For complete information, see the <xref:System.Text.CodePagesEncodingProvider> topic."},{"pos":[12533,12560],"content":"Selecting an Encoding Class","linkify":"Selecting an Encoding Class","nodes":[{"content":"Selecting an Encoding Class","pos":[0,27]}]},{"content":"If you have the opportunity to choose the encoding to be used by your application, you should use a Unicode encoding, preferably either <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.UTF8Encoding&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Text.UnicodeEncoding&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12564,12770],"source":"If you have the opportunity to choose the encoding to be used by your application, you should use a Unicode encoding, preferably either <xref:System.Text.UTF8Encoding> or <xref:System.Text.UnicodeEncoding>."},{"content":"(.NET also supports a third Unicode encoding, <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.UTF32Encoding&gt;</ph>.)","pos":[12771,12851],"source":" (.NET also supports a third Unicode encoding, <xref:System.Text.UTF32Encoding>.)"},{"content":"If you are planning to use an ASCII encoding (<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding&gt;</ph>), choose <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Text.UTF8Encoding&gt;</ph> instead.","pos":[12858,12986],"source":"If you are planning to use an ASCII encoding (<xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding>), choose <xref:System.Text.UTF8Encoding> instead."},{"content":"The two encodings are identical for the ASCII character set, but <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.UTF8Encoding&gt;</ph> has the 