aracters) to its numeric (byte) equivalent.","pos":[14887,14999]},{"content":"For example, you might use an ASCII encoder to convert Unicode characters to ASCII so that they can be displayed at the console.","pos":[15000,15128]},{"content":"To perform the conversion, you call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetBytes%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[15129,15245],"source":" To perform the conversion, you call the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetBytes%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":"If you want to determine how many bytes are needed to store the encoded characters before performing the encoding, you can call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetByteCount%2A&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[15246,15429],"source":" If you want to determine how many bytes are needed to store the encoded characters before performing the encoding, you can call the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetByteCount%2A> method."},{"content":"The following example uses a single byte array to encode strings in two separate operations.","pos":[15436,15528]},{"content":"It maintains an index that indicates the starting position in the byte array for the next set of ASCII-encoded bytes.","pos":[15529,15646]},{"content":"It calls the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetByteCount%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method to ensure that the byte array is large enough to accommodate the encoded string.","pos":[15647,15841],"source":" It calls the <xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetByteCount%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method to ensure that the byte array is large enough to accommodate the encoded string."},{"content":"It then calls the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetBytes%28System.String%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Byte%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method to encode the characters in the string.","pos":[15842,16061],"source":" It then calls the <xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetBytes%28System.String%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Byte%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method to encode the characters in the string."},{"content":"A decoder converts a byte array that reflects a particular character encoding into a set of characters, either in a character array or in a string.","pos":[16328,16475]},{"content":"To decode a byte array into a character array, you call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetChars%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[16476,16612],"source":" To decode a byte array into a character array, you call the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetChars%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":"To decode a byte array into a string, you call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetString%2A&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[16613,16712],"source":" To decode a byte array into a string, you call the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetString%2A> method."},{"content":"If you want to determine how many characters are needed to store the decoded bytes before performing the decoding, you can call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetCharCount%2A&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[16713,16896],"source":" If you want to determine how many characters are needed to store the decoded bytes before performing the decoding, you can call the <xref:System.Text.Encoding.GetCharCount%2A> method."},{"content":"The following example encodes three strings and then decodes them into a single array of characters.","pos":[16903,17003]},{"content":"It maintains an index that indicates the starting position in the character array for the next set of decoded characters.","pos":[17004,17125]},{"content":"It calls the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetCharCount%2A&gt;</ph> method to ensure that the character array is large enough to accommodate all the decoded characters.","pos":[17126,17288],"source":" It calls the <xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetCharCount%2A> method to ensure that the character array is large enough to accommodate all the decoded characters."},{"content":"It then calls the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetChars%28System.Byte%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Char%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method to decode the byte array.","pos":[17289,17498],"source":" It then calls the <xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding.GetChars%28System.Byte%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Int32%2CSystem.Char%5B%5D%2CSystem.Int32%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method to decode the byte array."},{"content":"The encoding and decoding methods of a class derived from <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoding&gt;</ph> are designed to work on a complete set of data; that is, all the data to be encoded or decoded is supplied in a single method call.","pos":[17765,17982],"source":"The encoding and decoding methods of a class derived from <xref:System.Text.Encoding> are designed to work on a complete set of data; that is, all the data to be encoded or decoded is supplied in a single method call."},{"content":"However, in some cases, data is available in a stream, and the data to be encoded or decoded may be available only from separate read operations.","pos":[17983,18128]},{"content":"This requires the encoding or decoding operation to remember any saved state from its previous invocation.","pos":[18129,18235]},{"content":"Methods of classes derived from <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoder&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Decoder&gt;</ph> are able to handle encoding and decoding operations that span multiple method calls.","pos":[18236,18410],"source":" Methods of classes derived from <xref:System.Text.Encoder> and <xref:System.Text.Decoder> are able to handle encoding and decoding operations that span multiple method calls."},{"content":"An <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.Encoder&gt;</ph> object 